replacing NAN values with mean:¶

it is a simple soloution to replacing NAN values with mean and it works totally fine. but when missing values are more than expected, it can reduce std and variance a lot and our data wont be accurate anymore.

completly deleting column containing missing values:¶

by doing this we guarantee that robust and highly accurate dataset this methos is very usefull when that column doesnt give extra info for our furthur calculation and when missing values are a lot.

in other hand by deleting whole column, we are losing some data that is inevitible.

def is_retired(passengers) -> bool :
    return(
        (passengers.Age > 35) &
        (passengers.Pclass == 3) &
        (passengers.SibSp == 0) &
        (passengers.Parch == 0)
    )

retired_passengers = passengers[is_retired(passengers)]

PDF of aliveness!¶

In [ ]:
from scipy.stats import norm
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

PLOT_ZOOM = 4

def plot_(alive_atr, dead_atr, column):
    alive_mean = alive_atr.mean() 
    alive_std = alive_atr.std() 
    dead_mean = dead_atr.mean()
    dead_std = dead_atr.std()

    x = np.linspace(alive_mean - PLOT_ZOOM * alive_std, alive_mean + PLOT_ZOOM * alive_std, 100)
    plt.plot(x, norm.pdf(x, alive_mean, alive_std))

    x = np.linspace(dead_mean - PLOT_ZOOM * dead_std, dead_mean + PLOT_ZOOM * dead_std, 100)
    plt.plot(x, norm.pdf(x, dead_mean, dead_std))

    plt.legend(['Alive', 'Dead'])
    plt.title(f'PDF of Alive and Dead passengers based on {column}')
    plt.show()

alive_passengers = passengers[passengers.Survived == 1]
dead_passengers =  passengers[passengers.Survived == 0]

for column in ["Age", "Parch", "Fare", "SibSp", "Pclass", "Embarked"]:
    plot_(alive_passengers[column], dead_passengers[column], column)

predict who is alive¶

chose attribute¶

in order to predict, we need to choose one of the attributes plotted above.

its best to cheose the one that has the most difference in mean value between alive and dead passengers and also the least difference in variance.

i choose "Fare" for some important reasons

In [ ]:
chosen_atr = "Fare"

read test file¶

In [ ]:
new_passengers = pd.read_csv("test.csv")

alive_mean = alive_passengers[chosen_atr].mean() 
alive_std = alive_passengers[chosen_atr].std() 
dead_mean = dead_passengers[chosen_atr].mean()
dead_std = dead_passengers[chosen_atr].std()

print(f"alive_mean : {alive_mean}")
print(f"alive_std : {alive_std}")
print(f"dead_mean : {dead_mean}")
print(f"dead_std : {dead_std}")

def condition(t):
    if (t < alive_mean + 1/4*alive_std) and t > (alive_mean - 1/4*alive_std):
        return "Alive"

    if (t < dead_mean + 1/4*dead_std) and t > (dead_mean - 1/4*dead_std):
        return "Dead"

    if (abs(t - alive_mean) < abs(t - dead_mean)):
        return "Alive"
    return "Dead"

new_passengers["Alive"] = np.nan
new_passengers["Alive"] = new_passengers[chosen_atr].apply(condition)

new_passengers[["PassengerId","Alive"]].to_csv("prediction.txt")
